A dart board is a regular hexagon divided into regions as shown. Suppose that a dart thrown at the board is equally likely to land anywhere on the board. What is the probability that the dart lands within the center hexagon, formed by connecting the midpoints of the sides of the outer hexagon?
{{DGM:e6a98b5eb33c1579}}
$\textbf{(A)}\ \frac{1}{3} \qquad \textbf{(B)}\ \frac{1}{4} \qquad \textbf{(C)}\ \frac{1}{5} \qquad \textbf{(D)}\ \frac{1}{6} \qquad \textbf{(E)}\ \frac{1}{7}$

Two circles in the same plane have radii $r$ and $R$ respectively, where $r \neq R$. Which of the following numbers of common tangents can these two circles not have?
{No choices provided here}
$\textbf{(A)} \ 0 \qquad \textbf{(B)} \ 1 \qquad \textbf{(C)} \ 2 \qquad \textbf{(D)} \ 3 \qquad \textbf{(E)} \ 4$
